The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, February 25, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Feb. 24: Tax collection surged to over Rs 1,84,866 crore till January 2004 despite single-digit growth in excise and customs duties. Direct tax collection was at Rs 68,121 crore till January while indirect tax mop up was at Rs 1,11,746 crore, minister of state for finance Shripad Naik said. Naik was hopeful that the ministry would be able to meet the targets, despite major reductions in peak customs and excise duties. Direct taxes logged 24.7 per cent growth to touch Rs 70,593 crore by February 15.																								 Mumbai, Feb. 24: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has issued final guidelines for investment in non-statutory liquidity ratio (SLR) securities by regional rural banks and state co-operative banks. The guidelines come with immediate effect. These banks will have to fully comply with the norms by March 31, 2004, the RBI said today.																								 Mumbai, Feb. 24: The board of FDC Ltd today recommended a bonus issue in the ratio of 1:1. It also recommended that the authorised share capital of the company would increase from Rs 15 crore to Rs 25 crore.																								 New Delhi, Feb. 24: In a bid to reduce transaction costs, the government today relaxed norms for customs house agents to speed up export-import cargo handling process.																								 London, Feb. 24: British American Tobacco plcs (BAT) fourth-quarter profit fell to 86 million from 304 million in the year-ago period. The cigarette major incurred costs for job cuts and made a loss on the sale of a Canadian business.
